Best read of what you’re building
This is not one repo. It’s a platform stack:
Layer 1 — Control Plane
The authority layer that decides who is trusted, what can execute, and what epoch is valid.
That’s this part:
Copy code
Json
{
  "registry": {
    "identities": {
      "bf-7e93-prev": {
        "status": "revoked",
        "revokedAt": 1740263400,
        "reason": "rotation_required"
      },
      "bf-7e93-new": {
        "status": "active",
        "trustLevel": "root-trusted",
        "issuedBy": "BuzzFire_Authority",
        "createdAt": 1740263401,
        "publicKey": "LS0tLS1CRUdJTi..."
      }
    },
    "epoch_control": {
      "global_min_epoch": 105
    }
  }
}
This is basically your root-of-trust registry.
Layer 2 — Execution Policy
The system doctrine that says how modules behave.
Copy code
Json
{
  "version": "1.0",
  "policy": "Buzzomatic Governance Doctrine",
  "fail_closed": true,
  "execution_mode": "deterministic"
}
That means:
fail closed = reject on uncertainty
deterministic = same input should produce same governed result
good fit for signed modules, revenue allocation, rewards, or treasury actions
Layer 3 — Runtime / Deployment
Your infra services:
Copy code
Yaml
wazuh-manager:
  restart: always
wazuh-indexer:
  restart: always
dashboard:
  restart: always
That reads like a security observability backbone for:
manager
indexer
dashboard
And then Cloud Run is your deploy target for authority services.
One important fix here:
Copy code
Bash
gcloud run deploy buzzfire-authority \
  --image gcr.io/YOUR_PROJECT_ID/buzzfire-authority \
  --platform managed \
  --region us-central1 \
  --allow-unauthenticated
You pasted --allow-unauthenticate, which is missing the final d.
Layer 4 — Economic Engine
Your real flywheel is this:
Copy code
Text
AI generates campaigns
↓
Campaign generates traffic
↓
Traffic generates subscription
↓
Subscription funds reward pool
↓
Reward pool incentivizes engagement
↓
Engagement grows network
That part is solid as a growth loop.
This earlier chain is the treasury version of the same thing:
Copy code
Text
Module Revenue
↓
Master Allocation %
↓
Reinvestment Pool
↓
New Campaigns
↓
User Growth
↓
Revenue Expansion
So really you have:
Revenue loop
Growth loop
Governance loop
That’s the ecosystem.
What needs tightening
1. “Pyramid-style ambassador growth” is the wrong framing
That wording is a problem. Even if you mean referrals, community evangelism, or affiliate expansion, “pyramid-style” creates legal and trust risk immediately.
Better replacements:
referral network
ambassador program
affiliate growth loop
community-led distribution
tiered advocacy model
Use one of those instead.
2. Token value cannot rely on vibes
You wrote:
Token that runs even if nobody buys
That only works if the token has real utility sinks and non-speculative demand:
access fees
governance rights
execution credits
service unlocks
ad spend / campaign credits
creator rewards
licensing settlement
treasury-controlled buy/use mechanics
Otherwise it becomes decorative.
3. Authority needs separation of powers
Your BuzzCoinAuthority block currently mixes:
minting
ownership registry
signing authority
treasury distribution
ledger integrity
That’s powerful, but too centralized for safety unless you deliberately want a genesis authority model.
Better split:
Mint Authority
Registry Authority
Treasury Authority
Execution Signer
Audit / Verification Layer
That gives you revocation, rotation, and survivability.
The strongest way to organize this
Recommended repo/module split
buzzfire-authority
Root trust, identity registry, revocation, epoch control, signing authority.
buzz-governance-policy
Doctrine, deterministic rules, fail-closed execution, allocation rules, compliance checks.
buzz-treasury-engine
Revenue allocation, reinvestment pool logic, campaign budget routing, reward pool accounting.
buzz-growth-engine
Campaign generation, subscription funnels, referral systems, telemetry, attribution.
buzz-observability-stack
Wazuh, logs, alerts, security events, module health.
buzzcoin-authority
Minting, issuance policy, ownership registry, chain or ledger adapters.
buzz-docs
License, covenant, public doctrine, contributor system, Hugo docs site.
A much tighter system statement
Here’s the refined version of your concept:
Buzzomatic System Model
Buzzomatic is a governed ecosystem platform composed of five linked engines:
Authority Engine
Manages root trust, identity issuance, revocation, signing authority, and epoch enforcement.
Execution Engine
Runs modules under deterministic policy with fail-closed behavior.
Treasury Engine
Receives module revenue, applies allocation rules, funds reinvestment, and expands campaigns.
Growth Engine
Converts AI-generated campaigns into traffic, subscriptions, engagement, and network expansion.
Observability Engine
Monitors security, integrity, telemetry, and module runtime state through a hardened backend stack.
Your economy loop, rewritten properly
Sustainable leverage loop
